While establishing a new connection as part of the check out process (i.e. when the pool is empty), the lock on the {{ConnectionManager}} is held. This prevents other tasks / threads from creating connections concurrently, which is a performance bottleneck and forbidden by CMAP:
{quote}
A Connection MUST NOT be checked out until it is readyToUse. In addition, the Pool MUST NOT block other threads from checking out connections while waiting for a connection to be readyToUse.
{quote}

We should release this lock while establishing connections to allow for more throughput and to become compliant with the spec.

Reproduced with client version 1.1.1 and mongodb server version 3.6.18

If a default write concern is set up on client:
{code}
let mut opts = ClientOptions::parse(&url).await?;
let wc = WriteConcern::builder().w(Acknowledgment::Majority).journal(true).build();
opts.write_concern = Some(wc);
let client = Client::with_options(opts)?;
{code}
And then that client is used to preform a command that doesn't support writeConcern:
{code}
client.database(db).collection(coll)
  .count_documents(filter, None).await?
{code}
Command will fail with an error:
{code}
Command failed (InvalidOptions): Command does not support writeConcern
{code}
I've tried to set some `CountOptions` instead of using None, but it did not help.

Workaround is to do not use a global WriteConcern, and set it on each request when needed, but IMO global wc is there for a reason, and this is a bug. Not sure if this is related to the somewhat ancient version of mongodb server I've tested this on, but it is officially supported by the rust driver as far as I know.

Due to the way the monitors clone the topology, release the read lock, update the topology, and then acquire the write lock and replace it wholesale, there is a race condition that could allow one monitor to overwrite the results of another, keeping a {{ServerDescription}} out of date until the next heartbeat.

